{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DVTKFdUdPQnaHKFB3CSdb2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"ES 8.11.1 is running and healthy (status: green, 3 nodes). The HTTPS API is working correctly.\n\nThe issue is that the readiness probe is failing, which means the pods are not marked as Ready, so the Kubernetes service doesn't route traffic to them.\n\nThe readiness probe I set uses:\n```yaml\nexec:\n  command:\n    - sh\n    - -c\n    - |\n      curl -sk -u \"elastic:${ELASTIC_PASSWORD}\" https://localhost:9200/_cluster/health?wait_for_status=yellow&timeout=1s | grep -q '\"status\":\"'\n```\n\nThe problem is the `&` in the URL is being interpreted as a shell background operator, so the curl command runs in the background while `timeout=1s` tries to execute as a separate command and fails. The environment variable `${ELASTIC_PASSWORD}` should be accessible in the exec probe's shell since Kubernetes passes the container's environment to the probe.\n\nThe real issue is just fixing the readiness probe definition so the pods become Ready. I could either use a TCP socket probe on port 9200 for simplicity, or fix the exec probe with proper URL quoting. A TCP probe would be cleaner since it just checks if the port is listening, avoiding the shell quoting complications.\n```","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":518,"cache_read_input_tokens":60108,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":518},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"039316f9-cb76-4b19-b32f-71a3b2658aed","uuid":"5daa6d0b-4040-452f-96eb-79696a80e782","request_id":"req_011CcM1jpG51vNWjbUcDrEin"}
